ata-sort-time="1578972597"><div id="div-comment-8085468" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong>dl90</strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2020/01/13/gavin-newsom-homelessness-billion-dollars/#comment-8085468">January.13.2020 at 10:29 pm </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>The science says otherwise.<br /> <a href="https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-ucla-anderson-forecast-20180613-story.html" rel="nofollow ugc">https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-ucla-anderson-forecast-20180613-story.html</a></p><p>In a study contained in the latest UCLA Anderson Forecast, released Wednesday, UCLA found that higher median rent and home prices are strongly correlated with more people living on the streets or in shelters. The research backs other studies that have found a similar relationship.</p><p>Last year, Zillow released a study that showed that a 5% rent hike in L.A. County  where more than 50,000 are estimated to be homeless  would cause 2,000 additional people to lose their homes.</p><p>If we can improve the affordability and the availability of the general housing market  I think it will help in reducing the homeless problem, said William Yu, the UCLA economist who conducted the research.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div><ol class="children"><li class="comment byuser odd alt depth-3 parent " id="comment-8085544" data-sort-time="1578979494"><div id="div-comment-8085544" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong>Overt</strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2020/01/13/gavin-newsom-homelessness-billion-dollars/#comment-8085544">January.14.2020 at 12:24 am </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>There is a lot of confusion and conflation of terms here. Yes, absolutely cost of housing does cause people to lose their homes. But the &#8220;Homeless&#8221; problem in California 